> We prefer baking our meatballs (rather than frying) because that way they
> get nice, plump, and juicy without heaps of oil. One bite and you'll be
> hooked on this combination of Asian-inspired flavors.

Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Lightly oil a
#baking sheet{}. Wash and dry all produce. Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb}
until you have ½ TBSP (1 TBSP for 4 servings). Trim and thinly slice
@scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; mince whites.

In a #small pot{}, combine ¾ cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings) and a
pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then stir in @jasmine rice{½%cup},
cover, and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.
Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, in a #medium bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce},
@panko breadcrumbs{¼%cup}, minced ginger, scallion whites,
@garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, and 2 TBSP water (3 TBSP for 4 servings). Season
with salt (we used ¾ tsp; 1 1/2 tsp for 4) and @pepper{}. Form into 1-inch balls
and place on prepared #baking sheet{}. Bake until meatballs are browned and
cooked through, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a second medium bowl, combine @hoisin sauce{6%tablespoon} and
2 TBSP water (3 TBSP for 4 servings). Once meatballs are cooked through,
carefully transfer to #bowl{} with hoisin mixture; toss to coat.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add @green beans{6%ounce} and cook, stirring, ~{3%minutes}. Add
2 TBSP water (4 TBSP for 4 servings) and cover pan with a #lid{} or
aluminum foil. Cook until tender, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Uncover and let water
evaporate. Season with salt and pepper.

Cut @lime{1} into wedges. Sprinkle meatballs with @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}.
Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} and season with salt
and pepper. Divide rice between plates and top with green beans and meatballs.
Garnish with scallion greens. Serve with lime wedges on the side.